Let the opponents of Ossian then point out to us poetry of equal merit with his, composed in any language, not an original one, and in a fictitious one, and referring to a nation and a history altogether fabulous. I suspect they would expose themselves to ridicule by the attempt. Many poets after Ossian endeavoured to copy or to imitate him ; but there is no man that understands our tongue, or the nature of our poetry, but will, on the first hearing of the first verses, easily distinguish their poems from his.
